==English==
===Etymology===
Unknown - see [[Talk:cock-and-bull story|discussion page]]

===Noun phrase===
'''[[cock]]-and-[[bull]] [[story]]''' (''plural'' '''cock-and-bull stories''')

#{{idiom}} A [[far-fetched]] and [[fanciful]] [[story]] or [[tale]] of highly [[dubious]] [[validity]]

From the  English Inns in Stoney Stratford, The Cock Inn and The Bull Inn sitting on the A5 Watling Street. In the 17th Century travellers rested at these Inns and exchanged extravagent tales. Only a few yards apart from the Bull the Cock had stables that exchanged horses for the next stage in the journey from London to the Midlands, hence the additional saying ` Ride a Cock Horse to Banbury Cross`. Banbury Cross was the next staging point in the journey.
The two Inns still exist today, however they are now on a pedestrian walkway in Stoney Stratford, Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, rich in history and Cock and Bull.

